;HOLODECKS
;
;ANCIENT CASTLE (HOLODECK PROGRAM)
NUMBER 3476
NAME Ancient Castle
REGION 1
INDOOR_FLOOR
FIXED_LIGHT
CAFE
MOVEMENT_ASTRAL
CHANNEL 777

CALL 49

RELOGIN 1920

ITEM 0 195 ADJ1=312
ITEM 1 196
ITEM 2 250
ITEM 3 194 ADJ1=298
ITEM 4 91 ADJ1=183 ADJ2=1225 ADJ3=216
PUT 4 1570 ADJ1=178 ADJ2=838 ADJ3=39 OPEN 
ITEM 5 86 ADJ1=1283 ADJ2=216
ITEM 6 1249 ADJ1=25 ADJ2=169
ITEM 7 358 ADJ1=178 ADJ2=143 OPEN
PUT 7 237 ADJ1=102 ADJ2=347 VAL2=100
ITEM 8 420
PUT 8 50 ADJ1=658 VAL5=9
PUT 8 45 ADJ1=241 VAL5=9

*DESCRIPTION_START
Snapping and crackling flames roar in a huge blaze from the massive stone
fireplace on your right, warming the air in this otherwise damp room. Heraldic
banners hang from the wooden beamed ceiling on either side of a black iron
chandelier, light from its dozens of sputtering flames flickering about the
room. A soft bearskin covers the floor between the log laden hearth and a long
sturdy oak table, surrounded by high backed wooden chairs. Glinting suits of
silvery armor and polished swords are displayed between the huge tapestries
lining the stone walls.
*DESCRIPTION_END

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 0
Huge bricks hewn from gray granite create the hearth for this ancient stone
fireplace. There is a huge blaze inside it at the moment. Beside a fresh supply
of logs stacked to one side is a poker in an iron stand.
*DESCRIPTION_END

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM IN 0
Several burning logs blaze inside the stone fireplace.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB POKE 0
   CLEARVERB
   ECHO PLAYER Using the poker, you stoke the blazing fire.
   ECHO OTHERS %N tends the fire with a poker.
ENDIF

IFTOUCH 0
   CLEARVERB
   ECHO PLAYER You extend your hands out in front of the flames warming your fingers.
   ECHO OTHERS %N warm %h hands before the fire.
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 1
The oaken logs are very dry and will kindle quickly.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB GET 1
   CLEARVERB
   ECHO PLAYER You pick up a log and add it to the blaze.
   ECHO OTHERS %N adds another log to the fire.
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 2
Several huge vibrantly woven tapestries depict life in a magical land. There
are people plowing fields, churning butter and tending their gardens. There is
a knight on a silver charger prancing toward a small castle nestled in a copse
of trees. The sky is filled with fire-breathing dragons and a lone wizard in a
pointed cap surveys the scene from a solitary peak.
*DESCRIPTION_END

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 3
It looks like aperfect place to stretch out in front of the warm fireplace
with someone special.
*DESCRIPTION_END

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 4
The sturdy oak table stretches almost from one end of the room to the other,
several high-backed wooden chairs surrounding it. Resting on top of the table
in front of each chair are large ruby-encrusted bronze goblets, while in the
center of the table is a large glass decanter filled with dry white wine.
*DESCRIPTION_END

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 5
Each chair has the face of the moon carved into its back. A crimson cushion
pads each seat.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB CLIMB 5
   CLEARVERB
   IFVAR FLAG1 = 0
      ECHO PLAYER You climb up on one of the high-backed wooden chairs.
      ECHO OTHERS %N climbs up on one of the high-backed wooden chairs.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR FLAG1 = 1
      ECHO PLAYER You're already standing in one of the chairs.
   ENDIF
   EQUAL FLAG1 1
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 6
Five iron arms, like spokes on a wheel, stretch out from the center of the
chandelier, rows of flickering candles ensconced along its surface. Suspended
high from the ceiling on sturdy chains, it hangs well out of your reach.
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB2 PUT 6
   CLEARVERB
   ECHO PLAYER The chandelier is too high to place anything on it. Even if you were to try
   ECHO PLAYER jumping from the chair, your chances of success are slim at best.
ENDIF

IFTOUCH 6
   IFVAR FLAG1 = 0
      CLEARVERB
      ECHO PLAYER The chandelier is well out of your reach.
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB GET 6
   IFVAR FLAG1 = 1
      CLEARVERB
      IFVAR ROUNDTIME ! 0
         STRCVT 0 ROUNDTIME
         ECHO PLAYER [Wait %0 seconds...]
      ENDIF
      IFVAR ROUNDTIME = 0
         EQUAL FLAG1 0
         EQUAL ROUNDTIME 10
         ECHO PLAYER You leap from the chair and try to grab the black iron chandelier...
         ECHO OTHERS %N leaps from the chair and tries to grab the black iron chandelier...
         PLREVENT 2
         CONTPLREVENT
         RANDOM DUMMY1 1 10 0
         IFVAR DUMMY1 > 5
            ECHO PLAYER but you miss and land sprawled out on the bearskin with a loud thud.
            ECHO OTHERS but %s misses and lands sprawled out on the bearskin with a loud thud.
            POSITION LAY
         ENDIF
         IFVAR DUMMY1 < 6
            ECHO PLAYER You miraculously manage to grab the edge of the chandelier and swing gracefully across the
room, landing on the other side of the table.
            ECHO OTHERS %N miraculously manages to grab the edge of the chandelier and swings gracefully across the
room, landing on the other side of the table.
         ENDIF
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
ENDIF

*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 7
The glass decanter contains some dry white wine. Why not fill a goblet and
have a refreshing sip?
*DESCRIPTION_END

IFPREVERB CLOSE 7
   CLEARVERB
   ECHO PLAYER The top to the decanter appears to be missing.
ENDIF

IFPREVERB LOOK -1
   IFVAR ARCHNUM = 50
      IFVAR ITEMVAL5 = 9
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO PLAYER You can almost imagine the valiant knights that wore this very armor, riding
         ECHO PLAYER off to battle astride their white steads, a reflection of the flickering flames
         ECHO PLAYER from the hearth causing a momentary illusion of a blazing battle scene.
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
   IFVAR ARCHNUM = 45
      IFVAR ITEMVAL5 = 9
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO PLAYER The large polished swords hang from the wall in pairs, their blades crossed
         ECHO PLAYER together. Though they are mostly for decoration, you are certain that they have
         ECHO PLAYER been kept razor-sharp.
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB TOUCH -1
   IFVAR ARCHNUM = 50
      IFVAR ITEMVAL5 = 9
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO PLAYER You decide it would be best not to disturb the armor.
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
   IFVAR ARCHNUM = 45
      IFVAR ITEMVAL5 = 9
         ECHO PLAYER You decide it would be best not to touch the swords.
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB GET -1
   IFVAR ARCHNUM = 1570
      IFVAR ITEMVAL5 ! 9
         CLEARVERB
         NEWITEM -1 1570 ADJ1=178 ADJ2=838 ADJ3=39 VAL5=9 OPEN 
         ECHO PLAYER You remove a goblet from the table.
         ECHO OTHERS %N removes a goblet from the table.
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB DRINK -1
   IFVAR ARCHNUM = 237
      IFVAR ITEMVAL2 = 100
         CLEARVERB
         ECHO PLAYER Drinking from the decanter? Why not from a goblet instead?
      ENDIF
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB SIT -1
   CLEARVERB
   IFVAR POSITION = 0
      ECHO PLAYER You take a seat on one of the chairs.
      ECHO OTHERS %N takes a seat on one of the chairs.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR POSITION = 1
      ECHO PLAYER You're already sitting.
   ENDIF     
   IFVAR POSITION = 2
      ECHO PLAYER You get up from the bearskin and sit in a chair.
      ECHO OTHERS %N gets up from the bearskin and sits in a chair.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR POSITION = 3
      ECHO PLAYER You take a seat on one of the chairs.
      ECHO OTHERS %N takes a seat on one of the chairs.
   ENDIF
   POSITION SIT
ENDIF

IFPREVERB LAY -1
   CLEARVERB
   IFVAR POSITION = 0
      ECHO PLAYER You lay down on the bearskin, stretching out comfortably in the soft fur.
      ECHO OTHERS %N lays down and stretches out on the bearskin.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR POSITION = 1
      ECHO PLAYER You move from the chair to lay on the bearskin.
      ECHO OTHERS %N get up from the chair and lays on the bearskin.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR POSITION = 2
      ECHO PLAYER You're already laying down.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR POSITION = 3
      ECHO PLAYER You lay down on the bearsking, stretching out comfortably in the soft fur.
      ECHO OTHERS %N lays down and stretches ou on the bearskin.
   ENDIF
   POSITION LAY
ENDIF

IFPREVERB LISTEN -1
   IFVAR ARCHNUM = -1
      CLEARVERB
      ECHO PLAYER You hear the crackle and roar of the fire.
      ECHO PLAYER %N listens.
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFPREVERB SNIFF -1
   CLEARVERB
   ECHO PLAYER You inhale the smokey castle air, tinged with the scent of the warming wine
   ECHO PLAYER in the decanter.
   ECHO OTHERS %N sniffs.
ENDIF

IFSAY LEAVE_PROGRAM
   IFVAR PLRSINROOM < 2
      ECHO PLAYER A soft voice from nowhere in tones, "You are on the only inhabitant of this
      ECHO PLAYER holodeck program. To leave, please say END PROGRAM and then exit the holodeck.
   ENDIF
   IFVAR PLRSINROOM > 1
      ECHO PLAYER A swirling light begins to surround you. When it fades, you find you are no
      ECHO PLAYER longer where you were before...
      ECHO OTHERS A swirling light begins to surround %N. When it fades, %s is no longer there.
      MOVE 1920
      AFFECT 1920
      ECHO OTHERS You hear a low hum, and then %N appears surrounded by a swirling light that soon fades.
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IFSAY END_PROGRAM
   ECHO ALL The scene fades instantly away...
   PLREVENT 1
   CONTPLREVENT
   EQUAL EXIT 3476
   CALL 38
ENDIF
